Core Structure of a C Program

Header Files (#include <stdio.h>)

The #include directive imports header files.

stdio.h (Standard Input Output) is mandatory for utilizing input and output functions. Without it, commands like printf will fail to compile.

The Main Function (int main())

Acts as the entry point for the program's execution.

int designates the function's return type (integer).

All executable code must reside within the curly braces {}.

Outputting Data (printf)

printf("Text"); is used to display strings to the screen.

Syntax Rule: Every standalone statement in C must terminate with a semicolon (;). Missing semicolons will trigger compilation errors.

Formatting Output (\n)

By default, multiple printf statements will output text on a single continuous line.

Use the newline character \n within the double quotes (e.g., printf("Hello\n");) to force the compiler to drop subsequent output to the next line.

Safe Exit (return 0;)

Because main() has an int return type, the program must return an integer value.

Returning 0 signals to the operating system that the program executed successfully without errors.
